BEL Leroux Algorithm

The metropolis hastings algorithm to draw samples of fixed effect \(\beta\) and spatial random effects \(\psi\) are drawn from simulated data set. Some data are generated as follows:

Response \(y\) was generated for each of the 2147 small reas across Australia. the spatial information to calculate the neighbourhood matrix are available to us.

Checking the output keeping psi fixed

To check the algorithm performance, we are not sampling the spatial random effect, keeping it fixed to the initial value. For skipping the burnin and checking the algorithm, we have initialised betas to its true value (intercept= 7, slope = 14).

The results of the algorithm are as follows:

## [1] "intercept"
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   6.665   6.825   6.942   6.905   6.983   7.037
## [1] "slope"
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   13.95   14.05   14.12   14.20   14.35   14.68

## [1] "Precision paramter"
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.02142 0.02902 0.03139 0.04830 0.03385 8.29524

So, the algorithm was able to estimate the true beta value. Now, we are changing the initial value of beta and taking an initial value from a multivariate normal prior.

Now, if we change the initial values of \(\beta\) from the true value to randomly generated values from prior distribution, the slope parameter can be estimated fine, but the intercept is not working well. That means there is still some bug in the algorithm that need fixing.
